{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 review — criterion T8 (LLM/agent structural-completeness probe). The overlay applies: the plan defines an authoring flow for plan-review *criteria* (rubrics) and *prompts* and surfaces overlay triggers. Two PROVEN structural gaps, plus affirmations of the parts that already hold.\n\nFINDING 1 (T8 — undefined-but-referenced enum/protocol vocabulary an executor needs)\n- [ ] Define the criterion-authoring form's full front-matter vocabulary (`category`, `execution_mode`, `dimension`), not just \"name + rubric/body\".\n  - criteria: T8\n  - location: AC line 3 (\"A user can author a new criterion AND a new prompt in-editor (name + rubric/body)\") + Scope bullet \"the authoring form\"\n  - evidence: The plan describes the criterion-authoring form as only \"name + rubric/body\". But a real packaged criterion (`src/rebar/llm/reviewers/plan_review_T8.md`, lines 1–9) carries `execution_mode: agentic`, `category: plan-review-criterion`, and `dimension: overlay-llm` in front-matter. The B-DM write validator (`src/rebar/llm/prompt_library.py:216–220`) REJECTS an unknown `execution_mode` (closed enum `EXECUTION_MODES = (\"single_turn\", \"agentic\")`, `src/rebar/llm/prompts.py:51`), and a criterion's `kind` is only `\"criterion\"` when `category == \"plan-review-criterion\"` (`prompt_library.py:127,59`). So the form must produce these enum-valued keys; their value vocabulary is referenced (by B-DM validation + by the criterion/prompt distinction) but never defined in the plan text. An executor authoring the form has no spec for which enum the form must offer.\n  - suggested_fix: In AC3 / the Scope authoring-form bullet, state that the criterion form sets `category: plan-review-criterion` and offers `execution_mode ∈ {single_turn, agentic}` (and decide whether `dimension` is author-supplied or defaulted), so the written `.md` passes B-DM validation and enumerates as kind=criterion.\n\nFINDING 2 (T8 — unspecified fallback for an incomplete sub-step; the \"author a new criterion\" path)\n- [ ] Specify what makes an authored criterion actually EXECUTE — referencing the new id in the step is not sufficient because the routing entry (`criteria_routing.json`) is out of B-DM scope.\n  - criteria: T8\n  - location: AC line 3 (\"written to the library via the B-DM API, the index is regenerated, and the new id is referenced in the step\") + AC line 4 (E2E \"author-new-criterion ... with persistence to the IR + library\")\n  - evidence: B-DM's own docstring states the gap explicitly: \"a user-authored criterion is ENUMERABLE here but is NOT executed by the plan-review gate unless it is in the canonical registry AND `criteria_routing.json` (routing derivation is out of scope for this write/enumerate layer)\" (`src/rebar/llm/prompt_library.py:173–175`; see also `enumerate_criteria`). The registry merges each criterion's library rubric with a routing entry carrying `exec`/`applies_at`/`block_threshold`/`default_posture`/`checklist` (`src/rebar/llm/plan_review/registry.py:9–37`), and the production batch runner reconstructs those per-criterion registry descriptors (`docs/design/batch-runner-seam.md:23–29`). A batch step references criteria by `prompt:` id (`tests/unit/workflow/test_batch_step.py:42`), so an authored criterion lacking a routing entry will be referenced but yield no valid descriptor at run time. The plan's \"the new id is referenced in the step\" leaves the routing/registry fallback for this sub-step unspecified — including what the AC4 E2E's \"persistence\" assertion should cover (library write only, or executable routing too).\n  - suggested_fix: Either (a) scope authored criteria to the editor-list/library only and state explicitly that executable routing is out of scope (so AC4's \"author-new-criterion ... persistence\" asserts the library `.md` + enumerate visibility, NOT gate execution), or (b) add the routing-entry write to AC3 so an authored criterion becomes executable; pick one and say so.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (T8 sub-checks that already hold)\n- \"No instruction-locality / pink-elephant antipattern; referenced agents/skills/enums exist\": the overlay-trigger `when` expression vocabulary IS fully grounded — the plan renders `${{ steps.<triggers>.outputs.<name> }}` against the real `overlay_triggers` step whose dynamic boolean output keys are exactly that (`src/rebar/schemas/overlay_triggers_output.schema.json`; `overlay_triggers_input.schema.json` defines keyword + structural trigger derivation), plus the \"(always include)\" option for the no-`when` case. No undefined trigger vocabulary.\n- \"A fallback for the create-trigger sub-step is specified\": inline create writes a `{name: [keywords]}` entry to the `overlay_triggers` step config, which then appears in the dropdown — co-located and complete (matches the `keyword_triggers` input contract).\n- The PROMPT-authoring path (vs. criterion) is fully specified for execution: a plain prompt needs only the B-DM-validated front-matter (`title`/`description`, optional `execution_mode`) and is resolvable via `get_prompt`/`enumerate_library` with no separate routing layer; the drift-gate-green claim is backed by B-DM's design (user writes never touch the committed packaged index — `prompt_library.py:25–35`, `tests/unit/test_prompt_library_writes.py:155–165`).\n\nA clean result on the two findings above (define the criterion front-matter enum vocabulary; specify the routing/execution fallback for authored criteria) would make this chunk fully pass T8."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782502286282176001,"uuid":"2b497050-437f-48e3-9112-782f5b54afd5"}